04350nam a22007335i 9780231541930DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20172016nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a2015044779  a97802315419307 a10.7312/urbi169842doi  a(DE-B1597)479856  a(OCoLC)979683331  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY00aJC423b.U77513 2016 7aPOL0070002bisacsh04a320.01/11 aUrbinati, Nadia, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Antiegalitarian Mutation :bThe Failure of Institutional Politics in Liberal Democracies /cNadia Urbinati, Arturo Zampaglione. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2017] 4c©2016  a1 online resource (200 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- t1. A Great Mutation -- t2. The Value of Democracy -- t3. The Decline of Universalism -- t4. The “Few” and the “Many” -- t5. The Secession from Democracy -- t6. Differences and Identity Politics -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe twin crises of immigration and mass migration brought new urgency to the balance of power between progressive, humanitarian groups and their populist opponents. In the United States and many European countries, the outcome of this struggle is uncertain, with a high chance that the public will elect more politicians who support an agenda of nativism and privatization. The Antiegalitarian Mutation makes a forceful case that those seeking to limit citizenship and participation, political or otherwise, have co-opted democracy. Political and legal institutions are failing to temper the interests of people with economic power against the needs of the many, leading to an unsustainable rise in income inequality and a new oligarchy rapidly assuming broad social control. For Nadia Urbinati and Arturo Zampaglione, this insupportable state of affairs is not an inevitable outcome of robust capitalism but rather the result of an ideological war waged against social democracy by the neoliberal governments of Reagan, Thatcher, and others. These giants of free-market fundamentalism secured power through legitimate political means, and only by taking back our political institutions can we remedy the social ills that threaten to unmake our world. That, according to The Antiegalitarian Mutation, is democracy's challenge and its ongoing promise.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aDemocracyzWestern countries. 0aSocial changexPolitical aspectszWestern countries. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Political ideologies / Democracy.2bisacsh1 aThom, Martin.1 aZampaglione, Arturo, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aZampaglione, Arturo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertColumbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311063857840uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/urbi1698440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780231541930423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780231541930.jpg  a978-3-11-063857-8  Columbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK